<subSubSection pageId="17" pageNumber="168" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="17.[151,1437,511,1149]" pageId="17" pageNumber="168">
<bibRefCitation author="Shoemaker, C. R." box="[151,357,511,537]" pageId="17" pageNumber="168" pagination="1 - 18" refId="ref17788" refString="Shoemaker, C. R. (1931) The Stegocephalid and Ampeliscid Amphipod Crustaceans of Newfoundland, Nova Scotia, and New Brunswick in t he United States National Museum. Proceedings of the United States National Museum, 79 (2888), 1 - 18, 6 figs. https: // doi. org / 10.5479 / si. 00963801.79 - 2888.1" type="journal article" year="1931">Shoemaker (1931)</bibRefCitation>
described 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Shoemaker" authorityYear="1931" box="[476,677,511,537]" class="Malacostraca" family="Ampeliscidae" genus="Haploops" kingdom="Animalia" order="Amphipoda" pageId="17" pageNumber="168" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="spinosa">
<emphasis box="[476,677,511,537]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="168">Haploops spinosa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in the amphipods collections of the 
<collectingCountry box="[1074,1223,511,537]" name="United States of America" pageId="17" pageNumber="168">United States</collectingCountry>
National Museum, indicating that this species is morphologically close to 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Liljeborg" authorityYear="1856" box="[765,891,547,573]" class="Malacostraca" family="Ampeliscidae" genus="Haploops" kingdom="Animalia" order="Amphipoda" pageId="17" pageNumber="168" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="tubicola">
<emphasis box="[765,891,547,573]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="168">H. tubicola</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, being often confused with it, but differs by several characters. He indicated that all the specimens studied were females, and the illustration of antennae, confirm that the specimens were females.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="17.[151,1437,511,1149]" pageId="17" pageNumber="168">
Later 
<bibRefCitation author="Kanneworff, E." box="[266,483,655,682]" pageId="17" pageNumber="168" pagination="183 - 207" refId="ref17294" refString="Kanneworff, E. (1966) On some amphipod species of the genus Haploops, with special reference to H. tubicola Liljeborg and H. tenuis sp. nov. from the Oresund. Ophelia, 3, 183 - 207." type="journal article" year="1966">Kanneworff (1966)</bibRefCitation>
stated that 
<taxonomicName authority="Shoemaker 1931" authorityName="Shoemaker" authorityYear="1931" box="[613,931,655,681]" class="Malacostraca" family="Ampeliscidae" genus="Haploops" kingdom="Animalia" order="Amphipoda" pageId="17" pageNumber="168" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="spinosa">
<emphasis box="[613,734,655,680]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="168">H. spinosa</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Shoemaker, C. R." box="[741,931,655,681]" pageId="17" pageNumber="168" pagination="1 - 18" refId="ref17788" refString="Shoemaker, C. R. (1931) The Stegocephalid and Ampeliscid Amphipod Crustaceans of Newfoundland, Nova Scotia, and New Brunswick in t he United States National Museum. Proceedings of the United States National Museum, 79 (2888), 1 - 18, 6 figs. https: // doi. org / 10.5479 / si. 00963801.79 - 2888.1" type="journal article" year="1931">Shoemaker 1931</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
was partly established because Shoemaker’s specimens differed from Sars’ illustrations of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Liljeborg" authorityYear="1856" box="[660,785,691,717]" class="Malacostraca" family="Ampeliscidae" genus="Haploops" kingdom="Animalia" order="Amphipoda" pageId="17" pageNumber="168" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="tubicola">
<emphasis box="[660,785,691,717]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="168">H. tubicola</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, and considered that the two species were synonymous. In his opinion Shoemaker was describing males of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Liljeborg" authorityYear="1856" box="[695,822,727,753]" class="Malacostraca" family="Ampeliscidae" genus="Haploops" kingdom="Animalia" order="Amphipoda" pageId="17" pageNumber="168" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="tubicola">
<emphasis box="[695,822,727,753]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="168">H. tubicola</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(as 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Shoemaker" authorityYear="1931" box="[869,989,727,752]" class="Malacostraca" family="Ampeliscidae" genus="Haploops" kingdom="Animalia" order="Amphipoda" pageId="17" pageNumber="168" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="spinosa">
<emphasis box="[869,989,727,752]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="168">H. spinosa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
). However, this assertion is not correct, if we consider the previous indications of 
<bibRefCitation author="Shoemaker, C. R." box="[622,814,763,789]" pageId="17" pageNumber="168" pagination="1 - 18" refId="ref17788" refString="Shoemaker, C. R. (1931) The Stegocephalid and Ampeliscid Amphipod Crustaceans of Newfoundland, Nova Scotia, and New Brunswick in t he United States National Museum. Proceedings of the United States National Museum, 79 (2888), 1 - 18, 6 figs. https: // doi. org / 10.5479 / si. 00963801.79 - 2888.1" type="journal article" year="1931">Shoemaker 1931</bibRefCitation>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="17.[151,1437,511,1149]" pageId="17" pageNumber="168">
<bibRefCitation author="Kanneworff, E." box="[199,419,799,826]" pageId="17" pageNumber="168" pagination="183 - 207" refId="ref17294" refString="Kanneworff, E. (1966) On some amphipod species of the genus Haploops, with special reference to H. tubicola Liljeborg and H. tenuis sp. nov. from the Oresund. Ophelia, 3, 183 - 207." type="journal article" year="1966">Kanneworff (1966)</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation author="Dickinson, J. J." box="[432,632,799,825]" pageId="17" pageNumber="168" refId="ref16912" refString="Dickinson, J. J. (1983) The systematics and distributional ecology of the superfamily Ampeliscoidea (Amphipoda: Gammaridea) in the northeastern Pacific region. 11. The genera Byblis and Haploops. Publications in Natural scicnces, National Museum of Natural Sciences. Vol. 1. National Museums of Canada, Ottawa, 38 pp., 17 figs, 6 tabs." type="book" year="1983">Dickinson (1983)</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation author="Barnard, J. L. &amp; Karaman, G. S." box="[645,958,799,825]" pageId="17" pageNumber="168" pagination="84 - 90" refId="ref16166" refString="Barnard, J. L. &amp; Karaman, G. S. (1991) The families and genera of marine Gammaridea Amphipod (except marine Gammaroid). Records of the Australian Museum, Supplement 13, Part 1, 84 - 90. https: // doi. org / 10.3853 / j. 0812 - 7387.13.1991.91" type="journal article" year="1991">Barnard &amp; Karaman (1991)</bibRefCitation>
had supported this synonymy between 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Shoemaker" authorityYear="1931" class="Malacostraca" family="Ampeliscidae" genus="Haploops" kingdom="Animalia" order="Amphipoda" pageId="17" pageNumber="168" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="spinosa">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="168">H. spinosa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Liljeborg" authorityYear="1856" box="[291,417,835,861]" class="Malacostraca" family="Ampeliscidae" genus="Haploops" kingdom="Animalia" order="Amphipoda" pageId="17" pageNumber="168" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="tubicola">
<emphasis box="[291,417,835,861]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="168">H. tubicola</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="17.[151,1437,511,1149]" pageId="17" pageNumber="168">
We have examined in detail some specimens from the BIOICE collections which show morphological characters close to the species described as 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Shoemaker" authorityYear="1931" box="[566,686,907,932]" class="Malacostraca" family="Ampeliscidae" genus="Haploops" kingdom="Animalia" order="Amphipoda" pageId="17" pageNumber="168" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="spinosa">
<emphasis box="[566,686,907,932]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="168">H. spinosa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by 
<bibRefCitation author="Shoemaker, C. R." box="[727,939,907,933]" pageId="17" pageNumber="168" pagination="1 - 18" refId="ref17788" refString="Shoemaker, C. R. (1931) The Stegocephalid and Ampeliscid Amphipod Crustaceans of Newfoundland, Nova Scotia, and New Brunswick in t he United States National Museum. Proceedings of the United States National Museum, 79 (2888), 1 - 18, 6 figs. https: // doi. org / 10.5479 / si. 00963801.79 - 2888.1" type="journal article" year="1931">Shoemaker (1931)</bibRefCitation>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
